    <fr:title text="preservation, lifting, reflection and creation of limits">preservation, lifting, reflection and creation of limits</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>
  Consider a functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F : \mathcal {C} \to  \mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
    <html:ul><html:li>If a limit cone <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is mapped to a limit cone in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>, then the functor <html:strong>preserves</html:strong> the limit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
  <html:li>If given a diagram <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> and a limit cone <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F \mathbin {\circ } D]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> can be extended to a limit cone in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> that maps to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>, then the functor <html:strong>lifts</html:strong> the limit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
  <html:li>If all the cones that maps to a limit cone <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex> are limit cones in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, then the functor <html:strong>reflects</html:strong> the limit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
  <html:li>If given a diagram <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> and a limit cone <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F \mathbin {\circ } D]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is reflected and lifted to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, then the limit of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is <html:strong>created</html:strong>.</html:li></html:ul>
    <html:p>
  This can be easily generalized to cover a type of limits or all limits, and can be dualized to colimits. The definitions here are not agreed upon, and the literature may have slight variations. We consider univalent categories here, so that definitions are automatically adjusted to be equivalence-invariant.
</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
